04160nam a2200493Ia 9780791481448DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780791481448  a(DE-B1597)682636  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBQ6353.K342bT656 2006eb 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a294.3/5708209521362221 aMorrell, Sachiko Kaneko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aZen Sanctuary of Purple Robes :bJapan's Tokeiji Convent Since 1285 /cSachiko Kaneko Morrell, Robert E. Morrell. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (266 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tWinds of Doctrine: The World of Thought and Feeling in Late Kamakura Japan -- tMujū Ichien’s Mirror for Women (Tsuma kagami, 1300): A Buddhist Vernacular Tract of the Late Kamakura Period -- tAbbess Kakusan and the Kamakura Hōjō -- tPrincess Yōdō’s Purple-clad Nuns -- tFrom Sanctuary to Divorce Temple: Abbess Tenshū and the Later Kitsuregawa Administrators -- tEveryday Life at Matsugaoka Tōkeiji: Sacred and Secular -- tThe “Divorce Temple” in Edo Satirical Verse -- tMeiji through Heisei: Tōkeiji and Rinzai Zen Continuity -- tAppendixes -- tNotes -- tAnnotated Cross-Referenced Index to Major Cited Texts -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aZen Sanctuary of Purple Robes examines the affairs of Rinzai Zen's Tōkeiji Convent, founded in 1285 by nun Kakusan Shidō after the death of her husband, Hōjō Tokimune. It traces the convent's history through seven centuries, including the early nuns' Zen practice; Abbess Yōdō's imperial lineage with nuns in purple robes; Hideyori's seven-year-old daughter—later to become the convent's twentieth abbess, Tenshu—spared by Tokugawa Ieyasu at the Battle for Osaka Castle; Tōkeiji as "divorce temple" during the mid-Edo period and a favorite topic of senryu satirical verse; the convent's gradual decline as a functioning nunnery but its continued survival during the early Meiji persecution of Buddhism; and its current prosperity. The work includes translations, charts, illustrations, bibliographies, and indices. Beyond such historical details, the authors emphasize the convent's "inclusivist" Rinzai Zen practice in tandem with the nearby Engakuji Temple. The rationale for this "inclusivism" is the continuing acceptance of the doctrine of "Skillful Means" (hōben) as expressed in the Lotus Sutra—a notion repudiated or radically reinterpreted by most of the Kamakura reformers. In support of this contention, the authors include a complete translation of the Mirror for Women by Kakusan's contemporary, Mujū Ichien.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDivorcezJapanxHistory. 0aWomen's shelterszJapanxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh1 aMorrell, Robert E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791481448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791481448/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles